  "prompt": "Is \"A Modest Proposal\" a parody?",
  "response": "Yes, \"A Modest Proposal\" by Jonathan Swift is often considered a work of parody, as well as satire. In the essay, Swift uses exaggerated and absurd suggestions\u2014proposing that the impoverished Irish might ease their economic troubles by selling their children as food\u2014to critique British policy toward Ireland and to draw attention to the dire social and economic conditions of the Irish populace.\n\nSwift's tone is deliberately ironic, and his shocking proposal serves to highlight the inhumanity of existing attitudes and solutions regarding poverty and overpopulation in Ireland. By presenting such an extreme solution, Swift effectively parodies the rational approaches that policymakers often promoted at the time. His work encourages readers to reflect on the moral implications of such proposals and the cruelty of indifference to human suffering. Thus, while it is a serious commentary on social issues, its use of irony and exaggeration places it firmly in the realm of parody and satire.",
